WEBVTT

1
00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:14.806
I believe that this nation should
commit itself to achieving the goal

2
00:00:14.890 --> 00:00:18.393
before this decade is out
of landing a man on the moon

3
00:00:18.477 --> 00:00:20.521
and returning him safely to the Earth.

4
00:00:21.855 --> 00:00:25.192
I don't think that we can exaggerate
the great advantage

5
00:00:25.275 --> 00:00:29.613
which the Soviet Union secured in the '50s
by being first in space.

6
00:00:30.739 --> 00:00:34.701
They were able to give prestige
to their system.

7
00:00:35.869 --> 00:00:37.788
They were able to give force
to their argument

8
00:00:37.871 --> 00:00:39.581
that they were an advancing society...

9
00:00:41.208 --> 00:00:42.709
...and that we were on the decline.

10
00:00:47.422 --> 00:00:50.259
Our great system will be judged

11
00:00:50.342 --> 00:00:52.719
by how we do in the field of space...

12
00:00:54.263 --> 00:00:55.806
and therefore this country.

13
00:00:56.765 --> 00:01:01.436
Both political parties have determined
that the United States shall be first.

14
00:01:05.566 --> 00:01:08.986
Quite obviously. if we fail.
we're humiliated.

15
00:01:09.069 --> 00:01:10.654
here and around the world.

16
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

17
00:01:27.462 --> 00:01:29.631
Aleida. my dear. Your mamma wants you.

18
00:01:35.053 --> 00:01:38.765
Still no further
word on the progress of the spacecraft

19
00:01:38.849 --> 00:01:40.475
toward the surface of the moon.

20
00:01:40.851 --> 00:01:44.938
But we believe that
it will be touching down any minute now.

21
00:01:45.022 --> 00:01:47.524
The last official report we have said

22
00:01:47.608 --> 00:01:49.776
that the landing vehicle was descending
toward the surface...

23
00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:51.111
Mama.

24
00:01:51.195 --> 00:01:53.280
How long do we have to watch this?

25
00:01:53.363 --> 00:01:54.364
Shh.

26
00:01:54.698 --> 00:01:56.825
They just talk. talk. talk...

27
00:01:56.909 --> 00:01:59.369
Aleida. This is special.

28
00:02:00.329 --> 00:02:02.748
You'll remember this
the rest of your life.

29
00:02:02.831 --> 00:02:05.626
This is the beginning of the future.

30
00:02:05.709 --> 00:02:07.753
You can be part of that.

31
00:02:07.836 --> 00:02:10.297
Maybe even go to the moon one day.

32
00:02:11.381 --> 00:02:13.550
You should be in bed.
The doctor says you need rest...

33
00:02:13.634 --> 00:02:15.719
Never mind the doctor.

34
00:02:15.802 --> 00:02:17.638
I want to be here for this.

35
00:02:18.472 --> 00:02:19.640
With her.

36
00:02:20.724 --> 00:02:22.017
So she'll remember.

37
00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:23.644
...the spacecraft has landed.

38
00:02:25.312 --> 00:02:26.980
Can we confirm that?

39
00:02:27.648 --> 00:02:28.857
Yes.

40
00:02:28.941 --> 00:02:31.193
They are on the moon.
ladies and gentlemen.

41
00:02:34.071 --> 00:02:37.449
Radio and television signals from the moon

42
00:02:37.533 --> 00:02:40.536
take less than two seconds
to reach us here on Earth.

43
00:02:40.619 --> 00:02:42.704
So if we do get television pictures.

44
00:02:42.788 --> 00:02:45.832
they'll be essentially broadcasting live.

45
00:02:46.625 --> 00:02:47.960
That's right.

46
00:02:48.043 --> 00:02:49.837
Live from the moon.

47
00:03:00.514 --> 00:03:03.934
In the United Kingdom. we're told
that Queen Elizabeth II was awakened...

48
00:03:05.853 --> 00:03:09.231
...when first reports
of the pending moon landing was received.

49
00:03:09.314 --> 00:03:11.358
And in Tokyo. Emperor Hirohito...

50
00:03:11.441 --> 00:03:13.569
Are they down?
The radio wasn't sure if they landed or...

51
00:03:13.652 --> 00:03:15.237
They're down. They're down.

52
00:03:15.904 --> 00:03:17.656
There's no video yet. but they're down.

53
00:03:17.739 --> 00:03:20.534
At the Vatican. Pope Paul VI positioned...

54
00:03:20.617 --> 00:03:23.328
One of the most shocking
events of my lifetime.

55
00:03:23.412 --> 00:03:26.748
This will shake things up in this country.
I'll tell you that right now.

56
00:03:26.832 --> 00:03:28.458
Things will never be the same.

57
00:03:50.022 --> 00:03:52.441
...are little more than guesswork.

58
00:03:52.524 --> 00:03:56.111
But experts have long anticipated
a possible viewership

59
00:03:56.195 --> 00:03:58.697
of over 500 million people.

60
00:03:58.780 --> 00:04:00.199
Is this really happening?

61
00:04:01.909 --> 00:04:04.203
I'm hearing we're getting a picture.

62
00:04:04.912 --> 00:04:07.164
Is that right? We have a picture?

63
00:04:07.748 --> 00:04:09.249
Sid. can we patch into...

64
00:04:10.417 --> 00:04:11.835
Got it.

65
00:04:11.919 --> 00:04:15.756
Ladies and gentlemen.
this is a live signal from the moon.

66
00:04:16.173 --> 00:04:18.091
Having some trouble seeing it.

67
00:04:19.635 --> 00:04:22.429
Uh... There. I see it. There it is.

68
00:04:24.097 --> 00:04:25.140
Amazing.

69
00:04:26.475 --> 00:04:27.976
Just unbelievable.

70
00:04:28.727 --> 00:04:32.147
The shock across the nation at this event.

71
00:04:32.231 --> 00:04:37.778
Indeed. the shock across the world
is just indescribable.

72
00:04:37.861 --> 00:04:41.281
What was considered a fantasy
just a short time ago

73
00:04:41.365 --> 00:04:44.159
is coming true right before our eyes.

74
00:04:45.327 --> 00:04:49.289
I believe we're looking at the legs
of the lunar lander.

75
00:04:50.165 --> 00:04:54.753
There at the bottom of your screen
is what appears to be a ladder.

76
00:04:55.295 --> 00:04:58.590
No word yet on when someone will be
climbing down that ladder. but...

77
00:04:58.674 --> 00:05:01.134
Wait. wait. Here we go.

78
00:05:01.218 --> 00:05:02.427
I see something.

79
00:05:03.345 --> 00:05:05.681
There he is. We have him.

80
00:05:06.306 --> 00:05:08.684
Oh. my goodness. Wow.

81
00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:11.103
Can you believe it?

82
00:05:12.145 --> 00:05:15.399
After thousands of years.
ladies and gentlemen.

83
00:05:15.482 --> 00:05:18.735
gazing up in the heavens
and dreaming of this day.

84
00:05:19.736 --> 00:05:23.282
a man is about to set foot on the moon.

85
00:05:39.214 --> 00:05:42.134
Don't know what he's saying. obviously.

86
00:05:42.217 --> 00:05:45.304
but we'll get a translation of his words.

87
00:05:46.180 --> 00:05:50.517
man's first words from the moon.
in just a minute.

88
00:05:53.228 --> 00:05:56.356
Okay. we have the translation now.

89
00:05:56.440 --> 00:06:01.695
and these are the words
that Cosmonaut Alexei Leonov.

90
00:06:01.778 --> 00:06:04.448
the first man to set foot on the moon.

91
00:06:04.531 --> 00:06:06.408
spoke just moments ago.

92
00:06:06.992 --> 00:06:10.913
"I take this step for my country.
for my people.

93
00:06:10.996 --> 00:06:14.208
and for the Marxist-Leninist way of life.

94
00:06:14.291 --> 00:06:17.294
Knowing that today is but one small step

95
00:06:17.377 --> 00:06:22.007
on a journey that someday
will take us all to the stars."

96
00:06:30.265 --> 00:06:31.934
I'm not sure what to say.

97
00:06:32.017 --> 00:06:34.478
Perhaps there are no words.

98
00:06:35.103 --> 00:06:37.147
So. for now.

99
00:06:37.231 --> 00:06:39.816
we'll let you soak in
this historic moment...

100
00:06:41.193 --> 00:06:44.279
and reflect on what it means
for our country...

101
00:06:45.489 --> 00:06:47.074
and for the world.

102
00:08:15.996 --> 00:08:16.955
How the hell did this happen?

103
00:08:17.664 --> 00:08:20.918
Those bastards at NASA have been acting
like they had everything under control.

104
00:08:21.001 --> 00:08:23.003
and then they fumble the ball
right at the goddamn goal line.

105
00:08:23.086 --> 00:08:23.921
Right at the goal!

106
00:08:24.004 --> 00:08:25.797
Yes. sir. it sure looks that way.

107
00:08:25.881 --> 00:08:29.426
CIA is working up a review of their intel
over the last year

108
00:08:29.510 --> 00:08:31.720
to see if they missed any signs
of Soviet advances that...

109
00:08:31.803 --> 00:08:33.472
They missed
the whole goddamn thing!

110
00:08:33.554 --> 00:08:34.890
The whole match!

111
00:08:34.972 --> 00:08:36.808
You know how the press is gonna play this.
don't you?

112
00:08:37.058 --> 00:08:38.477
The New York Times is going to say that

113
00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:40.145
Kennedy started the moon race.

114
00:08:40.354 --> 00:08:41.188
Johnson ran it.

115
00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:42.981
and then Nixon tripped at the goal line.

116
00:08:43.065 --> 00:08:44.024
That's what it's gonna be.

117
00:08:44.691 --> 00:08:46.777
They're gonna try and hang this
around my neck.

118
00:08:47.277 --> 00:08:48.278
but they're not gonna succeed.

119
00:08:48.570 --> 00:08:49.363
No. sir.

120
00:08:49.446 --> 00:08:51.156
I'll tell you that right goddamn now.

121
00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:52.616
Not Nixon.

122
00:09:07.256 --> 00:09:09.967
Shane. let's go.
Shake a leg. Bus is almost here.

123
00:09:11.844 --> 00:09:13.554
- Last day of school?
- Next week.

124
00:09:14.179 --> 00:09:16.056
One more week to go. sailor.

125
00:09:16.139 --> 00:09:17.140
Yeah. I know.

126
00:09:17.641 --> 00:09:18.642
What?

127
00:09:19.226 --> 00:09:20.978
- I mean. yes. sir.
- That's right.

128
00:09:23.939 --> 00:09:25.524
They shoulda let you land.

129
00:09:26.358 --> 00:09:27.776
then we woulda been first.

130
00:09:31.947 --> 00:09:34.575
Yeah. Well. that wasn't my mission. buddy.

131
00:09:36.201 --> 00:09:37.619
Hey. Here's your lunch. okay?

132
00:09:37.703 --> 00:09:39.288
- Let's get going.
- Thank you.

133
00:09:39.580 --> 00:09:40.664
Hey. you have a good day. okay?

134
00:09:40.747 --> 00:09:42.249
- Yeah. Bye. Dad.
- Bye-bye.

135
00:09:42.791 --> 00:09:44.543
Love you. sweetie. Have a good day.

136
00:09:45.169 --> 00:09:46.336
- Thank you.
- Okay.

137
00:09:52.342 --> 00:09:54.636
So. how do you think
it's gonna affect the program?

138
00:09:56.638 --> 00:09:59.266
I don't know. Deke's called
an all-hands meeting this morning.

139
00:09:59.349 --> 00:10:01.351
So. I guess we'll find out then.

140
00:10:04.855 --> 00:10:06.690
I hope they still fly Apollo 15.

141
00:10:07.274 --> 00:10:08.984
Yeah.

142
00:10:09.067 --> 00:10:10.068
Me too.

143
00:10:11.403 --> 00:10:13.864
Hey. do you want me
to save this or toss it?

144
00:10:13.947 --> 00:10:14.948
Toss it.

145
00:10:17.201 --> 00:10:18.202
Okay.

146
00:10:18.410 --> 00:10:19.411
Ah...

147
00:10:20.162 --> 00:10:21.163
Save it.

148
00:11:28.021 --> 00:11:29.356
- Morning. Poppy.
- Morning.

149
00:11:30.107 --> 00:11:31.775
- Morning. sir.
- Morning.

150
00:11:46.164 --> 00:11:49.084
Apollo 11 is scheduled to fly
in two and a half weeks.

151
00:11:49.168 --> 00:11:53.589
Neil. Buzz. Mike and their backup crew
will continue training as planned.

152
00:11:53.672 --> 00:11:55.632
Beyond that.
there's been no word from the top.

153
00:11:55.716 --> 00:12:00.929
So. training for Apollos 12 to 20
will also continue as planned...

154
00:12:02.264 --> 00:12:03.599
but not today.

155
00:12:07.853 --> 00:12:10.480
I was at the Cape
with the rest of the Mercury astronauts

156
00:12:10.564 --> 00:12:15.152
when Jim Webb came down and told us
the Russians put the first man in space.

157
00:12:15.235 --> 00:12:18.280
Webb wanted us
to put a good face on for the press.

158
00:12:18.363 --> 00:12:21.241
So we did. but not for a while.

159
00:12:22.159 --> 00:12:23.911
First. we had to be pissed off.

160
00:12:23.994 --> 00:12:25.370
and we were.

161
00:12:26.246 --> 00:12:29.124
Gus could hardly speak. And Al...

162
00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.668
Glad Al Shepard's not here today.

163
00:12:31.752 --> 00:12:34.630
Al was really pissed. Even Glenn.

164
00:12:34.713 --> 00:12:36.131
Yes. believe it or not. gentlemen.

165
00:12:36.215 --> 00:12:38.383
John Glenn actually said the word "fuck."

166
00:12:44.139 --> 00:12:47.392
So before we go back to work.
it's time to be pissed!

167
00:12:49.603 --> 00:12:52.481
All training evolutions for today
have been canceled.

168
00:12:54.316 --> 00:12:58.737
I suggest you all take the weekend
to go out. get drunk.

169
00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:01.114
kick your dog.
gnash your teeth. howl at the moon.

170
00:13:01.198 --> 00:13:03.200
or do whatever suits your purpose.

171
00:13:06.495 --> 00:13:07.996
Come Monday morning...

172
00:13:12.125 --> 00:13:13.335
we're back to work.

173
00:13:16.171 --> 00:13:17.297
That is all.

174
00:13:39.278 --> 00:13:41.530
So. Outpost?

175
00:13:44.533 --> 00:13:45.701
Last one buys.

176
00:14:41.548 --> 00:14:42.633
Ah!

177
00:15:29.555 --> 00:15:30.639
Pam.

178
00:15:40.774 --> 00:15:41.942
All right. Fine.

179
00:15:45.529 --> 00:15:47.322
-  Pam! Pam!
- All right!

180
00:15:49.283 --> 00:15:50.534
Come on up. Pam.

181
00:15:51.577 --> 00:15:53.745
- Set it off. Set it off.

182
00:15:55.706 --> 00:15:57.249
- Pam. throw it.
- No!

183
00:16:05.340 --> 00:16:07.134
- One more round?
-  Yeah!

184
00:16:11.346 --> 00:16:13.932
The president wants answers.
and he wants them now.

185
00:16:14.808 --> 00:16:19.188
We at NASA were given no indication
the Soviets were so close to a landing.

186
00:16:19.271 --> 00:16:22.983
The intelligence provided by the CIA
was faulty and inaccurate.

187
00:16:23.066 --> 00:16:24.401
Hold on now. Wait a minute.

188
00:16:24.985 --> 00:16:26.486
Langley's not taking the fall for this.

189
00:16:26.570 --> 00:16:29.406
We did report two launches
of the Soviet N-1 rocket.

190
00:16:29.489 --> 00:16:32.075
One launch in January.
and then one this past week.

191
00:16:32.159 --> 00:16:34.411
Both launches were duly noted
in our intel reports to you.

192
00:16:34.494 --> 00:16:36.288
You said they were unmanned tests.

193
00:16:36.371 --> 00:16:40.083
We said we had a 95% confidence level
the January vehicle was unmanned.

194
00:16:40.167 --> 00:16:42.920
But we only had 80% confidence
on the second launch.

195
00:16:43.003 --> 00:16:44.588
Only 80%.

196
00:16:44.671 --> 00:16:46.715
The president must understand

197
00:16:46.798 --> 00:16:50.594
that our technology is vastly superior
to the Russians'.

198
00:16:50.677 --> 00:16:53.514
The N-1 is a crude
and unsophisticated vehicle

199
00:16:53.597 --> 00:16:55.182
compared to the Saturn V.

200
00:16:55.265 --> 00:16:57.267
All the president cares about right now

201
00:16:57.351 --> 00:17:00.437
is getting an American on the moon
as soon as possible.

202
00:17:00.521 --> 00:17:02.731
Can you move up the launch of Apollo 11?

203
00:17:06.026 --> 00:17:07.653
The vehicle could be ready.

204
00:17:08.278 --> 00:17:10.030
but the phase of the moon
would not be correct.

205
00:17:10.405 --> 00:17:12.324
The phase of the moon? Come on.

206
00:17:12.406 --> 00:17:13.617
He's right.

207
00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:15.827
If the phase of the moon is not correct.

208
00:17:15.911 --> 00:17:18.204
there won't be enough light
on the surface.

209
00:17:18.288 --> 00:17:20.374
And we cannot land in darkness.

210
00:17:21.375 --> 00:17:22.376
Shit.

211
00:17:23.417 --> 00:17:27.130
Our program is much more robust.
more capable in every way.

212
00:17:27.214 --> 00:17:30.968
We will not only match the Soviets.
we will surpass them.

213
00:17:31.927 --> 00:17:36.306
NASA is prepared to extend
manned exploration beyond the moon.

214
00:17:37.182 --> 00:17:40.269
Mankind's journey into the cosmos
has only just begun.

215
00:17:40.352 --> 00:17:41.854
- Yes?

216
00:17:41.937 --> 00:17:44.606
Deke. just last month you sent Apollo 10
all the way to the moon

217
00:17:44.690 --> 00:17:47.276
for what you called a "dress rehearsal"
for the landing.

218
00:17:48.110 --> 00:17:51.196
But Ed Baldwin and Gordo Stevens
actually piloted the lunar module

219
00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:53.991
down to within eight miles of the surface.

220
00:17:54.074 --> 00:17:55.284
They were so close.

221
00:17:55.367 --> 00:17:56.910
Why didn't they just land?

222
00:17:56.994 --> 00:17:59.371
If they had. we'd have beaten the Russians
by a full month.

223
00:17:59.913 --> 00:18:01.832
Landing wasn't in the mission plan.

224
00:18:01.915 --> 00:18:06.336
Apollo 10 was intended to test equipment
and procedures for the actual landing.

225
00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:07.921
And it was a complete success.

226
00:18:08.005 --> 00:18:10.090
But they could've landed. right?

227
00:18:10.716 --> 00:18:11.884
They could've been first.

228
00:18:11.967 --> 00:18:15.596
An American. Edward Baldwin.
could have been the first man on the moon.

229
00:18:15.679 --> 00:18:17.097
No. this is not true.

230
00:18:17.681 --> 00:18:20.517
There was insufficient fuel
for such an attempt.

231
00:18:20.601 --> 00:18:23.187
And the spacecraft weighed too much
for a landing.

232
00:18:23.270 --> 00:18:25.189
It was never considered. Never.

233
00:18:25.272 --> 00:18:26.440
Yes?

234
00:18:29.693 --> 00:18:30.694
How we doin'?

235
00:18:38.660 --> 00:18:40.495
George. good to see ya.

236
00:18:40.579 --> 00:18:41.663
- How ya feelin'?
- Hey.

237
00:18:44.166 --> 00:18:45.751
How we doing today. fellas? Huh?

238
00:18:45.834 --> 00:18:48.504
Not at all? You don't have a comment
at all about any of this?

239
00:18:48.587 --> 00:18:49.588
No comment.

240
00:18:49.671 --> 00:18:51.465
- Zero?
- Zero comment.

241
00:18:51.548 --> 00:18:53.300
- That's...
- What's there to talk about?

242
00:18:53.383 --> 00:18:55.010
I couldn't think of a thing.

243
00:18:55.093 --> 00:18:57.429
All right. I'll buy the next round.
okay? Thanks.

244
00:19:00.098 --> 00:19:01.099
What's up. big man?

245
00:19:01.934 --> 00:19:03.769
- Hey. how we doing today?
- Good. man.

246
00:19:03.852 --> 00:19:05.896
Good to see you again. Good to see you.

247
00:19:05.979 --> 00:19:07.314
- It's kinda shitty.
- Kinda shitty. Right.

248
00:19:07.397 --> 00:19:09.149
That's what I've been hearing
from everyone else.

249
00:19:09.233 --> 00:19:10.234
Can you give me something?

250
00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:12.361
You don't need that.

251
00:19:13.362 --> 00:19:14.488
Well. what about you two?

252
00:19:14.571 --> 00:19:17.741
Any thoughts from the crew of Apollo 10
on this dark day?

253
00:19:17.824 --> 00:19:20.202
Not a one.
We're just here blowing off some steam.

254
00:19:20.285 --> 00:19:22.746
Come on. You guys were pretty close.

255
00:19:23.539 --> 00:19:25.874
Got eight miles above the surface.

256
00:19:26.959 --> 00:19:30.546
So close you just reach out
and grab a handful of moondust.

257
00:19:30.629 --> 00:19:32.923
And then NASA decides
to bring you home.

258
00:19:34.091 --> 00:19:35.342
That must sting.

259
00:19:37.636 --> 00:19:38.637
Don't matter.

260
00:19:42.474 --> 00:19:45.060
That was our mission.
It was a practice run.

261
00:19:45.143 --> 00:19:46.353
Dress rehearsal.

262
00:19:47.521 --> 00:19:48.689
Wasted opportunity?

263
00:19:51.775 --> 00:19:52.901
Wouldn't go that far.

264
00:19:53.819 --> 00:19:57.114
Well. you were there. Are you saying
there wasn't an opportunity to land?

265
00:19:57.197 --> 00:19:58.699
Not in the mission plan.

266
00:19:59.157 --> 00:20:02.452
Yeah. okay. Fair enough.
But in retrospect. should it have been?

267
00:20:02.536 --> 00:20:04.121
I mean. knowing what you know now.

268
00:20:04.204 --> 00:20:07.082
wouldn't the smart move have been
for Apollo 10 to land on the moon?

269
00:20:12.838 --> 00:20:14.089
It's not a matter of smarts.

270
00:20:15.716 --> 00:20:16.717
Yeah.

271
00:20:17.467 --> 00:20:19.761
Yeah. I guess not.
NASA's full of smart people.

272
00:20:21.221 --> 00:20:22.931
Of course.
I guess it's a moot point

273
00:20:23.015 --> 00:20:26.560
since there wasn't enough fuel on board.
and the LEM was too heavy to land anyway.

274
00:20:26.643 --> 00:20:27.811
Bunch of bullshit.

275
00:20:27.895 --> 00:20:29.897
Snoopy was heavier than Eagle.

276
00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:31.857
Had a little less fuel.

277
00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:34.776
But all that means is we woulda had
a little narrower safety margin

278
00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:36.403
if we'd gone for the landing.

279
00:20:36.486 --> 00:20:38.488
- Ain't that right. Ed?
- That's a fact.

280
00:20:39.823 --> 00:20:41.033
I gotta hit the head.

281
00:20:50.667 --> 00:20:52.711
So. Ed.

282
00:20:52.794 --> 00:20:54.796
if you had the right equipment

283
00:20:54.880 --> 00:20:56.548
and you had the opportunity.

284
00:20:56.632 --> 00:20:58.717
and NASA is full of smart people.

285
00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:00.677
what I can't figure is...

286
00:21:02.054 --> 00:21:06.808
why they didn't have the guts
to let you land.

287
00:21:07.392 --> 00:21:08.519
- Huh?

288
00:21:08.602 --> 00:21:10.020
You got some balls. man.

289
00:21:10.103 --> 00:21:11.396
I'm just saying.

290
00:21:11.480 --> 00:21:14.441
I mean. NASA's always been known
for its willingness to push the envelope.

291
00:21:25.410 --> 00:21:27.079
I wanna just reach down there.

292
00:21:27.955 --> 00:21:30.165
Scoop up a handful of moondust.

293
00:21:39.132 --> 00:21:41.134
Not anymore.

294
00:21:43.345 --> 00:21:45.472
Come on. I've been around you guys a lot.

295
00:21:46.098 --> 00:21:48.350
You like being
on the bleeding edge of things.

296
00:21:48.433 --> 00:21:50.185
Abort Descent Stage.

297
00:21:50.644 --> 00:21:53.772
Three. two... one...

298
00:22:07.703 --> 00:22:08.871
We used to.

299
00:22:09.997 --> 00:22:11.415
We used to be like that.

300
00:22:11.832 --> 00:22:13.458
I mean. hell. in Mercury and Gemini.

301
00:22:13.542 --> 00:22:17.212
we hung it out there over the edge
every single time we went up.

302
00:22:17.296 --> 00:22:20.048
But those days are over.

303
00:22:23.093 --> 00:22:26.305
You're right.
We don't have guts at NASA anymore...

304
00:22:29.641 --> 00:22:30.809
since the fire.

305
00:22:32.936 --> 00:22:34.104
The Apollo 1 fire.

306
00:22:36.773 --> 00:22:39.067
Okay. I loved those guys. all right. I...

307
00:22:40.277 --> 00:22:43.947
Gus and Roger and Ed...

308
00:22:47.409 --> 00:22:49.786
I think about them every day.
I mean. we all do.

309
00:22:49.870 --> 00:22:51.163
They were good men.

310
00:22:52.664 --> 00:22:56.293
That's the thing.
Good men die in test planes all the time.

311
00:22:56.376 --> 00:23:00.797
But we don't change the whole culture
of flight test 'cause good men die.

312
00:23:02.299 --> 00:23:05.010
We still get up there
and push the envelope every single day.

313
00:23:05.093 --> 00:23:06.970
and maybe.

314
00:23:07.763 --> 00:23:10.557
maybe today's the day you don't come back.

315
00:23:11.266 --> 00:23:13.227
We all know that. It's always there.

316
00:23:13.310 --> 00:23:15.896
But we get up there anyway.
and we keep taking the risks.

317
00:23:17.898 --> 00:23:19.858
But we stopped taking risks at NASA.

318
00:23:24.571 --> 00:23:26.740
And that's why we lost the moon.

319
00:23:36.250 --> 00:23:37.251
Thanks. Ed.

320
00:24:05.863 --> 00:24:06.905
Aleida!

321
00:24:09.366 --> 00:24:10.784
It's time to go!

322
00:24:44.610 --> 00:24:47.029
Houston. Eagle.
We have a program alarm.

323
00:24:50.616 --> 00:24:51.950
It's a 12-02.

324
00:24:53.285 --> 00:24:55.037
Copy that. 12-02.

325
00:24:58.457 --> 00:25:00.584
Stand by. Eagle. We're checking.

326
00:25:00.667 --> 00:25:04.838
In the meantime. yaw the antenna
around minus niner. yaw plus 18.

327
00:25:04.922 --> 00:25:07.674
Copy. Minus nine. plus 18.

328
00:25:16.600 --> 00:25:18.644
GUIDO. what's the story with that alarm?

329
00:25:18.727 --> 00:25:21.396
Uh. checking on it. Flight.
Get right back to ya.

330
00:25:48.882 --> 00:25:51.718
GUIDO. this is Margo.
I think I recognize that alarm.

331
00:25:51.802 --> 00:25:53.595
It's okay. They can still land.

332
00:25:54.221 --> 00:25:56.557
Margo. you're outta your lane.
This is a GUIDO issue.

333
00:25:59.434 --> 00:26:00.561
I know the code.

334
00:26:01.395 --> 00:26:05.357
Twelve-02 is a program alarm for the AGC
signaling "Executive overflow. no VAC."

335
00:26:06.024 --> 00:26:09.027
The computer is rebooting itself.
but it's not a problem.

336
00:26:16.952 --> 00:26:18.871
Houston. we need a reading on the 12-02.

337
00:26:19.496 --> 00:26:21.623
- GUIDO!
- Still don't have it. Flight.

338
00:26:25.752 --> 00:26:27.963
Okay. I'm calling it.

339
00:26:28.922 --> 00:26:29.923
Abort the landing.

340
00:26:30.007 --> 00:26:32.050
Eagle. Houston. abort.
Repeat. Abort landing.

341
00:27:00.913 --> 00:27:02.289
The fault is yours.

342
00:27:02.789 --> 00:27:04.750
Why? Because I wasn't in my lane?

343
00:27:04.833 --> 00:27:06.251
Because you hesitated.

344
00:27:07.503 --> 00:27:09.505
I wanted to double-check my answer.

345
00:27:09.588 --> 00:27:11.006
You knew the answer.

346
00:27:11.590 --> 00:27:13.926
you hesitated.
and the landing was aborted.

347
00:27:14.426 --> 00:27:17.471
You're always telling me that
I have to respect the chain of command.

348
00:27:17.554 --> 00:27:18.847
- Yes.
- Well. in this situation.

349
00:27:18.931 --> 00:27:20.224
I felt the chain of command...

350
00:27:20.307 --> 00:27:23.227
No. not "feel."
This is not a place for feelings.

351
00:27:23.310 --> 00:27:25.896
Something is or it is not.
That is science.

352
00:27:25.979 --> 00:27:27.272
It's about fact.

353
00:27:27.356 --> 00:27:31.902
You had the facts on your side.
but you felt intimidated.

354
00:27:33.487 --> 00:27:34.488
Yes?

355
00:27:35.948 --> 00:27:37.115
- Yes?
- Yes.

356
00:27:38.700 --> 00:27:40.869
Well. that is the problem.

357
00:27:42.871 --> 00:27:44.331
You want to be a flight controller.

358
00:27:45.040 --> 00:27:46.917
to be FIDO on a real mission?

359
00:27:48.961 --> 00:27:52.256
Then you must only do
that which advances the work.

360
00:27:53.257 --> 00:27:54.258
Understand?

361
00:28:03.934 --> 00:28:06.895
Yes. Herr Doktor.

362
00:28:08.105 --> 00:28:09.106
Good.

363
00:28:09.982 --> 00:28:12.150
Tell your father
I'm sending something for his birthday.

364
00:28:12.234 --> 00:28:14.528
but he won't get it until after.

365
00:28:15.654 --> 00:28:16.780
I will.

366
00:28:19.950 --> 00:28:21.076
"We were right there.

367
00:28:21.159 --> 00:28:25.497
So close you felt like you could reach out
and grab a handful of moondust.

368
00:28:25.581 --> 00:28:27.291
All it would've taken was some guts.

369
00:28:27.374 --> 00:28:29.710
But we don't have guts at NASA anymore.

370
00:28:29.793 --> 00:28:32.379
That's why we didn't beat the Russians
to the moon."

371
00:28:38.051 --> 00:28:40.053
You are in the shit now. my friend.

372
00:28:40.804 --> 00:28:41.930
How deep?

373
00:28:42.014 --> 00:28:43.515
Above your eyeballs.

374
00:28:45.559 --> 00:28:48.896
Von Braun wants you reassigned
to the Apollo Applications Project

375
00:28:48.979 --> 00:28:50.731
effective immediately.

376
00:28:50.814 --> 00:28:52.941
Are you taking me off Apollo 15?

377
00:28:53.650 --> 00:28:56.403
You took you off 15.

378
00:28:57.821 --> 00:28:59.865
Von Braun wanted you
outta the program completely.

379
00:28:59.948 --> 00:29:01.658
but I wouldn't let him go that far.

380
00:29:06.121 --> 00:29:07.456
Apollo Applications.

381
00:29:09.333 --> 00:29:12.503
Apollo Applications is Siberia
with a desk.

382
00:29:13.670 --> 00:29:15.255
I didn't say anything in that article

383
00:29:15.339 --> 00:29:17.508
that you and I haven't talked about
in this very office.

384
00:29:17.591 --> 00:29:20.511
- Jesus Christ.
- We have gotten too timid since the fire.

385
00:29:20.594 --> 00:29:23.430
We should be leaning forward instead
of worrying about every little goddamn...

386
00:29:23.514 --> 00:29:25.015
Pull your head outta your ass. Ed!

387
00:29:26.016 --> 00:29:27.184
Look around!

388
00:29:27.684 --> 00:29:30.646
You wanna cry about Apollo 15?
Let me tell you something.

389
00:29:30.729 --> 00:29:33.273
There may not be an Apollo 12.
much less 15.

390
00:29:34.107 --> 00:29:35.442
What the hell are you talking about?

391
00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:39.196
The country's in shock. Eddie.

392
00:29:39.905 --> 00:29:41.573
Like Pearl Harbor shock.

393
00:29:42.324 --> 00:29:44.326
American people thought
we had this thing in the bag.

394
00:29:44.409 --> 00:29:47.329
then the Russians come along
and snatch it away at the last minute.

395
00:29:48.413 --> 00:29:50.457
Congress is talking about hearings.

396
00:29:50.541 --> 00:29:52.584
the president is looking
for someone to blame.

397
00:29:52.668 --> 00:29:55.420
and you just served up
the whole goddamn agency

398
00:29:55.504 --> 00:29:56.964
for a necktie party.

399
00:29:58.632 --> 00:30:02.427
They really might
cancel everything after 11?

400
00:30:03.262 --> 00:30:05.848
That's usually what happens
when the race is over.

401
00:30:05.931 --> 00:30:07.891
Winner collects their prize.

402
00:30:07.975 --> 00:30:09.351
loser goes home.

403
00:30:12.396 --> 00:30:15.691
Senator Edward Kennedy
of Massachusetts announced today

404
00:30:15.774 --> 00:30:19.736
that he was canceling a weekend party
on Chappaquiddick Island

405
00:30:19.820 --> 00:30:24.616
in order to return to Washington
and confer with congressional leaders

406
00:30:24.700 --> 00:30:26.118
on the need for hearings

407
00:30:26.201 --> 00:30:30.122
into how the United States
lost the race to the moon.

408
00:30:32.165 --> 00:30:33.917
You know what Teddy's
really doing. don't you?

409
00:30:34.501 --> 00:30:36.336
That goddamn pissant's
gonna use these hearings

410
00:30:36.420 --> 00:30:38.255
to grandstand against the administration.

411
00:30:38.505 --> 00:30:39.464
Yep...

412
00:30:39.548 --> 00:30:42.759
Gonna get up there and say
how NASA was bolder under his brother...

413
00:30:42.968 --> 00:30:44.803
How they've lost their edge under Nixon...

414
00:30:44.887 --> 00:30:45.804
Uh-huh.

415
00:30:45.888 --> 00:30:47.347
This is the opening
of the campaign.

416
00:30:47.890 --> 00:30:50.184
Kennedy for President in '72...
just you watch.

417
00:30:50.601 --> 00:30:52.436
God help us all.

418
00:31:01.737 --> 00:31:03.864
I guess I'll start packing.

419
00:31:05.657 --> 00:31:06.700
Right?

420
00:31:07.701 --> 00:31:10.871
I mean. if you can't fly for NASA.
you'll go back to the navy.

421
00:31:12.956 --> 00:31:14.666
I don't know what I'm gonna do yet.

422
00:31:16.126 --> 00:31:17.794
Well. are you gonna sit behind a desk?

423
00:31:20.297 --> 00:31:21.882
- Hell no.
- Exactly.

424
00:31:21.965 --> 00:31:24.885
So. you'll go back to the navy.
which means we're moving.

425
00:31:24.968 --> 00:31:27.137
The next question now is where.

426
00:31:28.722 --> 00:31:31.016
I don't know.
are you gonna ask for Pax River?

427
00:31:31.099 --> 00:31:33.268
I mean. Maryland's fine.

428
00:31:34.186 --> 00:31:35.354
It beats Texas. I suppose.

429
00:31:35.437 --> 00:31:37.814
I'm sure that Shane will grow to love it.

430
00:31:38.732 --> 00:31:41.360
Look. I doubt they're gonna have
an open slot on the flight test

431
00:31:41.443 --> 00:31:43.195
just waiting for me to waltz in.

432
00:31:46.198 --> 00:31:48.575
Okay. and if that's the case...

433
00:31:50.702 --> 00:31:53.580
you'll ask for carrier duty then. right?

434
00:31:53.664 --> 00:31:55.499
Commander of your own fighter squadron?

435
00:31:55.582 --> 00:31:58.293
Which means. based on your past.

436
00:31:58.377 --> 00:32:00.295
they will send you back to Seventh Fleet.

437
00:32:00.379 --> 00:32:02.005
which means we'll be based out of Pearl.

438
00:32:02.089 --> 00:32:04.132
I mean. housing isn't great.

439
00:32:04.216 --> 00:32:07.010
but it's Oahu.
so you can't complain. right?

440
00:32:07.094 --> 00:32:08.554
Not that you'll see much of Oahu.

441
00:32:08.637 --> 00:32:12.474
because you'll be commanding your squadron
on your carrier on Yankee Station.

442
00:32:12.558 --> 00:32:14.309
flying strike missions over Vietnam.

443
00:32:14.393 --> 00:32:15.644
It's what I do. Karen.

444
00:32:15.727 --> 00:32:17.980
That is a goddamn useless thing to say.

445
00:32:28.490 --> 00:32:30.868
I didn't know
it was gonna blow up like this.

446
00:32:31.952 --> 00:32:35.205
Why? Because you were
just two guys in a bar

447
00:32:35.289 --> 00:32:36.999
talking and telling it like it is?

448
00:32:37.082 --> 00:32:38.834
- Something like that.
- To a reporter!

449
00:32:40.043 --> 00:32:43.297
I thought there was
supposed to be this code.

450
00:32:44.006 --> 00:32:47.843
The pilot's code that says you're not
supposed to talk about your feelings.

451
00:32:48.343 --> 00:32:51.597
Like. how you might feel
about not landing on the moon.

452
00:32:51.680 --> 00:32:55.309
or. I don't know. how you feel
about the whole damned space program.

453
00:32:56.059 --> 00:32:58.729
The code says you're not supposed
to talk about those things.

454
00:32:59.438 --> 00:33:01.106
That's what you said.
Not with your buddies.

455
00:33:01.190 --> 00:33:03.483
not with your family. not with your wife.

456
00:33:03.567 --> 00:33:05.444
- This has nothing to do...
- I mean. who knew?

457
00:33:06.653 --> 00:33:09.656
Who knew that all it took
was a couple of drinks in a dive bar

458
00:33:09.740 --> 00:33:11.200
for you to break that code?

459
00:33:12.034 --> 00:33:13.702
I'm gonna learn to drink with the guys.

460
00:33:13.785 --> 00:33:16.997
Yeah. 'cause then I can find out
how my husband really feels about his job.

461
00:33:17.080 --> 00:33:20.000
Or I'll just read about it
in the newspapers with everyone else!

462
00:33:22.586 --> 00:33:23.587
Right?

463
00:34:21.687 --> 00:34:22.688
Your neck?

464
00:34:22.771 --> 00:34:25.690
Yeah. Couch is too damn small.

465
00:34:27.275 --> 00:34:28.569
I like it that way.

466
00:34:30.779 --> 00:34:31.864
Why is that?

467
00:34:34.366 --> 00:34:35.868
So there's no other choice.

468
00:35:20.204 --> 00:35:21.538
The hell y'all looking at?

469
00:35:23.916 --> 00:35:26.877
You never seen a lowly pudknocker
from Apollo Applications?

470
00:35:38.764 --> 00:35:39.890
Look. uh.

471
00:35:39.973 --> 00:35:45.604
I know there was some dumb son of a bitch

472
00:35:45.687 --> 00:35:50.275
that shot his mouth off in the press
and made the whole agency look bad.

473
00:35:52.528 --> 00:35:54.071
But I also know that

474
00:35:54.154 --> 00:35:57.824
the crew of Apollo 11 is gonna make
everyone forget about all that.

475
00:35:58.534 --> 00:36:01.662
Because Neil. Buzz. Mike.

476
00:36:01.745 --> 00:36:06.500
they're the kind of guys
who don't fold when things get tough.

477
00:36:09.628 --> 00:36:12.756
They're the kinda guys
that might get knocked down...

478
00:36:14.550 --> 00:36:19.513
but then they just pick themselves up
and get back to work.

479
00:36:29.314 --> 00:36:33.402
So. I'm here to help you boys
get back to work.

480
00:36:33.485 --> 00:36:34.778
Any way I can.

481
00:36:34.862 --> 00:36:37.614
From Siberia...

482
00:36:39.741 --> 00:36:44.538
I bring you adjusted fuel
and payload calculations for the S-IVB.

483
00:36:58.051 --> 00:37:00.721
I think Siberia...

484
00:37:03.182 --> 00:37:04.558
sits over there.

485
00:37:27.539 --> 00:37:29.082
Two weeks to launch. gentlemen.

486
00:37:29.708 --> 00:37:32.127
This will be our last meeting
before 11 heads for the Cape.

487
00:37:32.211 --> 00:37:34.004
so I want final checklists on my desk.

488
00:37:42.513 --> 00:37:44.097
So. will he make the call?

489
00:37:44.932 --> 00:37:45.933
I don't know.

490
00:37:46.016 --> 00:37:48.602
Ziegler said the president wants to call
the astronauts on the moon.

491
00:37:48.685 --> 00:37:51.480
but I think they're
leaving themselves some wiggle room.

492
00:37:51.563 --> 00:37:55.025
But it's another chance to demonstrate
the superiority of our technology.

493
00:37:55.776 --> 00:37:57.319
The Russian audio was terrible.

494
00:37:57.819 --> 00:38:01.323
We will call a man on the moon
from a telephone. I mean. it's amazing.

495
00:38:01.406 --> 00:38:03.534
I told them. You know what Ziegler said?

496
00:38:04.409 --> 00:38:07.287
"The president doesn't usually call
the silver medalist."

497
00:38:07.371 --> 00:38:08.372
Got it!

498
00:38:11.041 --> 00:38:13.001
It wasn't easy. but I got it.

499
00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:16.338
Just glad we remembered.

500
00:38:16.964 --> 00:38:20.092
Just as well. It was always extra weight.

501
00:38:26.974 --> 00:38:28.058
Pilots.

502
00:38:28.725 --> 00:38:30.644
We should have stuck with the monkeys.

503
00:38:35.482 --> 00:38:37.025
Almost a month has passed

504
00:38:37.109 --> 00:38:40.654
since the historic landing
of a Soviet cosmonaut on the moon

505
00:38:40.737 --> 00:38:42.155
shocked the world.

506
00:38:42.239 --> 00:38:46.910
During that time. the crew of Apollo 11
has continued to train and prepare

507
00:38:46.994 --> 00:38:49.955
for their own historic landing
on the lunar surface.

508
00:38:51.081 --> 00:38:53.792
While the Nixon administration has made
no public commitment

509
00:38:53.876 --> 00:38:55.544
to any landing beyond this one.

510
00:38:55.627 --> 00:38:58.088
multiple anonymous sources
in the White House have said

511
00:38:58.172 --> 00:39:00.465
that if Apollo 11 were to end in failure.

512
00:39:00.549 --> 00:39:03.260
the entire program
would probably be canceled.

513
00:39:29.828 --> 00:39:32.247
This is Apollo Saturn Launch Control.

514
00:39:32.331 --> 00:39:34.917
The crew are aboard the spacecraft.
the hatch is closed.

515
00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.794
and everything seems
to be proceeding satisfactorily.

516
00:39:38.253 --> 00:39:41.256
In just a few moments. there will be
a scheduled hold in the count

517
00:39:41.340 --> 00:39:44.009
at exactly T-minus two hours.

518
00:39:44.092 --> 00:39:47.554
Built-in hold in five. four.

519
00:39:47.638 --> 00:39:51.183
three. two. one.

520
00:39:51.266 --> 00:39:52.267
Holding.

521
00:39:52.351 --> 00:39:55.229
The count has been held
at T-minus two hours.

522
00:39:55.312 --> 00:39:57.689
Flight Director Gene Kranz
is now giving last-minute...

523
00:39:57.773 --> 00:40:00.192
Jim. I want you to bring in the backups
and lock the doors.

524
00:40:00.275 --> 00:40:02.402
- Cut the video and the mics.
- You got it. Flight.

525
00:40:21.672 --> 00:40:24.633
Till a few weeks ago.
I thought I knew what today was all about.

526
00:40:26.593 --> 00:40:28.512
I thought it was about being first.

527
00:40:30.138 --> 00:40:32.349
Turns out
the stakes are much bigger than that.

528
00:40:33.934 --> 00:40:36.478
Today is about the future of our country.

529
00:40:37.229 --> 00:40:38.397
The future of the world.

530
00:40:39.690 --> 00:40:42.526
Because if we fail in our mission today.

531
00:40:42.609 --> 00:40:45.362
the United States will
turn away from space.

532
00:40:46.363 --> 00:40:47.823
turn away from the future.

533
00:40:48.699 --> 00:40:52.286
Bogged down by war. poverty. hatred.

534
00:40:54.705 --> 00:40:55.998
And the future?

535
00:40:57.332 --> 00:40:59.376
Well. the future will belong
to the Soviet Union.

536
00:41:00.043 --> 00:41:03.589
They will be the ones
reaching into space for all of mankind.

537
00:41:05.632 --> 00:41:08.093
Now. I want you all to think about that
for a moment.

538
00:41:10.679 --> 00:41:13.182
What that means for the future.

539
00:41:13.265 --> 00:41:16.351
to look like
the "Marxist-Leninist way of life."

540
00:41:20.564 --> 00:41:22.316
But if we succeed.

541
00:41:23.525 --> 00:41:26.904
if we succeed
in putting Apollo 11 on the moon.

542
00:41:27.905 --> 00:41:29.239
we're still in this thing.

543
00:41:29.323 --> 00:41:31.450
Still in the race.

544
00:41:31.533 --> 00:41:35.454
The future will be ours
to fight for and to win.

545
00:41:37.414 --> 00:41:39.208
We put a man on the moon today.

546
00:41:39.291 --> 00:41:41.835
I guarantee we are not stopping there.

547
00:41:42.961 --> 00:41:45.756
We'll go to Mars. Saturn.

548
00:41:46.173 --> 00:41:49.176
The asteroids. the stars. deep space.

549
00:41:49.968 --> 00:41:51.094
The galaxy.

550
00:41:52.638 --> 00:41:56.517
And then. then we're getting answers
to the big questions.

551
00:41:58.268 --> 00:42:01.438
Are we alone? Is there life out there?

552
00:42:04.566 --> 00:42:08.529
I am proud to be a member of this team.

553
00:42:09.947 --> 00:42:12.866
and I know that we will succeed today
in our mission...

554
00:42:13.951 --> 00:42:18.038
in putting two Americans on the moon.

555
00:42:18.830 --> 00:42:23.085
Because in this room. in this agency.

556
00:42:23.669 --> 00:42:25.254
in this country...

557
00:42:27.339 --> 00:42:29.132
failure is not an option.

558
00:42:43.146 --> 00:42:45.566
Kennedy Launch Control.
we are go for launch.

559
00:42:46.233 --> 00:42:49.111
Copy. Houston.
We are resuming the countdown.

560
00:43:11.842 --> 00:43:14.094
Flying for almost four days.

561
00:43:14.178 --> 00:43:19.808
the American spacecraft known as the Eagle
is on course toward the lunar surface.

562
00:43:19.892 --> 00:43:25.189
The spacecraft carrying
Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin

563
00:43:25.272 --> 00:43:27.399
is now now flying on its own power.

564
00:43:27.858 --> 00:43:32.404
It should start its descent
in approximately one hour.

565
00:43:39.036 --> 00:43:41.538
Why don't you
give us an idea of the landing stage

566
00:43:41.622 --> 00:43:43.540
of the lunar module in the Eagle?

567
00:43:44.082 --> 00:43:47.878
After separation.
the LEM will perform a pitch-up maneuver.

568
00:43:47.961 --> 00:43:50.547
then the two spacecraft will
back away from one another...

569
00:43:50.631 --> 00:43:52.674
Don't get too rowdy with the boys. okay?

570
00:43:52.758 --> 00:43:54.384
Try to behave.

571
00:43:54.468 --> 00:43:56.970
Well. hey. Shane. Have a seat. Welcome.

572
00:43:57.846 --> 00:43:59.556
- Hey. Come on in.
- Thanks.

573
00:43:59.640 --> 00:44:01.517
- Can I take your purse?
- No. I'll set it down.

574
00:44:02.142 --> 00:44:06.313
...a short burn. which will send them
down towards the surface.

575
00:44:06.980 --> 00:44:09.358
...attempting this dangerous landing.

576
00:44:20.160 --> 00:44:21.161
Cheers.

577
00:44:21.912 --> 00:44:24.122
To Snoopy and what might have been.

578
00:44:29.962 --> 00:44:33.131
You ever think about
what you would have said if it'd been you?

579
00:44:35.133 --> 00:44:38.303
- What's that?
- If you were the first man on the moon.

580
00:44:39.304 --> 00:44:40.681
Probably something better than

581
00:44:40.764 --> 00:44:43.934
"I'm here for the Marxist-Leninist
way of fucking life." I'm sure.

582
00:44:46.478 --> 00:44:47.688
Never thought about it.

583
00:44:49.273 --> 00:44:50.566
Come on. Never?

584
00:44:51.859 --> 00:44:53.694
- Never once.
- Oh.

585
00:44:55.779 --> 00:44:57.114
I thought about it a lot.

586
00:44:57.823 --> 00:44:59.199
- Oh. yeah?
- Mmm.

587
00:45:00.242 --> 00:45:01.785
So. what would you have said. Gordo?

588
00:45:02.286 --> 00:45:03.495
- Thanks. Pam.
- Anytime. Ed.

589
00:45:03.579 --> 00:45:06.915
Well. first I thought. you know.
maybe quote one of the classics.

590
00:45:06.999 --> 00:45:09.376
Aristotle. Plutarch. Voltaire.

591
00:45:09.459 --> 00:45:10.502
Dean Martin.

592
00:45:12.504 --> 00:45:16.216
But then I thought. no.
it should be about today. Now.

593
00:45:16.300 --> 00:45:20.345
You know. the whole world seems
like it's tearing itself apart.

594
00:45:20.429 --> 00:45:23.682
War. death. hate.

595
00:45:25.100 --> 00:45:26.768
Chicago. last year.

596
00:45:27.394 --> 00:45:29.479
Man. Chicago last year.

597
00:45:30.022 --> 00:45:32.191
I never seen anything like that before.

598
00:45:33.150 --> 00:45:36.820
I love that city. I went to school there.
I had a bunch of friends. you know?

599
00:45:36.904 --> 00:45:39.615
And to be back there on those streets
where I went to school

600
00:45:39.698 --> 00:45:41.325
and see it all go down like that?

601
00:45:41.408 --> 00:45:44.119
You know.
the cops just beating on those kids?

602
00:45:44.912 --> 00:45:47.122
You remember? You know?

603
00:45:47.789 --> 00:45:50.167
Just crushing their heads
with their batons

604
00:45:50.250 --> 00:45:52.127
and just blood everywhere and they...

605
00:45:52.211 --> 00:45:53.879
I just never seen that before.

606
00:45:56.131 --> 00:46:00.135
To see the hate in their eyes.

607
00:46:01.220 --> 00:46:04.806
You know. they wanted to kill those kids.
They wanted to crush them.

608
00:46:04.890 --> 00:46:07.434
Right? Like they were just bugs.

609
00:46:08.101 --> 00:46:10.395
And I thought to myself. "You know. maybe.

610
00:46:10.479 --> 00:46:13.398
maybe a man being up on the moon...

611
00:46:15.400 --> 00:46:19.947
might make people like that
just lift their eyes for a moment

612
00:46:20.030 --> 00:46:23.408
and look past that hate
and see something bigger.

613
00:46:25.285 --> 00:46:26.411
Bigger like...

614
00:46:28.580 --> 00:46:29.665
hope."

615
00:46:34.002 --> 00:46:35.546
So. what would you have said. Gordo?

616
00:46:36.922 --> 00:46:38.882
- Hmm?
- What would you have said?

617
00:46:39.633 --> 00:46:40.801
Um...

618
00:46:42.386 --> 00:46:43.387
Uh...

619
00:46:44.263 --> 00:46:45.472
I would've said...

620
00:46:46.765 --> 00:46:49.268
I'm Gordo Stevens and I come in peace.

621
00:46:54.690 --> 00:46:56.191
Three times a night.

622
00:47:03.657 --> 00:47:05.534
-  You're a stupid idiot.

623
00:47:07.327 --> 00:47:10.247
You're a stupid. stupid man.

624
00:47:10.330 --> 00:47:11.498
You had me.

625
00:47:25.470 --> 00:47:26.680
Eagle. Columbia. Houston.

626
00:47:26.763 --> 00:47:29.266
All systems are looking good
for going over the hill.

627
00:47:29.349 --> 00:47:30.726
Ten seconds to LOS.

628
00:47:31.351 --> 00:47:32.394
Roger that.

629
00:47:32.477 --> 00:47:35.063
Roger that.
Houston. Talk to you on the other side.

630
00:47:46.033 --> 00:47:49.578
Loss of signal of Apollo 11.
Reacquisition in 48 minutes.

631
00:47:53.081 --> 00:47:54.583
Good time for a head call.

632
00:47:59.713 --> 00:48:02.841
It's pretty disturbing.
but it was really good.

633
00:48:03.217 --> 00:48:04.968
- Mmm.
- You know. it sticks with you.

634
00:48:06.303 --> 00:48:07.471
Jon Voight is amazing.

635
00:48:08.680 --> 00:48:10.599
What did Gordo think
of this movie?

636
00:48:10.682 --> 00:48:13.435
Oh. he was just upset
that it wasn't that kind of X-rated film.

637
00:48:13.519 --> 00:48:14.603
Of course he was.

638
00:48:14.686 --> 00:48:17.022
Marge. It's so good to see you.

639
00:48:17.481 --> 00:48:18.690
Well. well. well.

640
00:48:19.274 --> 00:48:20.984
The queen has arrived.

641
00:48:21.068 --> 00:48:23.820
- I thought you said she wasn't coming.
- I assumed she wasn't.

642
00:48:23.904 --> 00:48:25.781
If I had known
Deke's wife was gonna show up.

643
00:48:25.864 --> 00:48:27.866
I would've had the butler
bring out the good silver.

644
00:48:27.950 --> 00:48:30.410
- Hello. Karen.
- Hello.

645
00:48:30.494 --> 00:48:31.787
- Tracy.
- Marge.

646
00:48:32.287 --> 00:48:33.413
Are you busy right now?

647
00:48:34.331 --> 00:48:35.332
Not at all.

648
00:48:35.415 --> 00:48:36.917
Good. Excuse us.

649
00:48:38.919 --> 00:48:40.504
- Napkin.
- Thanks.

650
00:48:41.088 --> 00:48:44.132
It's a small spacecraft
for three grown men to live in full-time.

651
00:48:44.842 --> 00:48:46.468
- Should we sit down?
-  Sure.

652
00:48:58.397 --> 00:49:02.234
Everyone believes it would be
in the best interests of the agency...

653
00:49:03.485 --> 00:49:05.153
and the country

654
00:49:05.237 --> 00:49:07.865
for Edward to make a public denial.

655
00:49:08.574 --> 00:49:13.954
stating emphatically that
he was grossly misquoted by that reporter

656
00:49:14.037 --> 00:49:17.916
and strongly disassociating himself
from those remarks.

657
00:49:23.505 --> 00:49:26.300
I also think. in that instance.

658
00:49:27.926 --> 00:49:31.805
Deke would be able to persuade
Dr. von Braun to reinstate him on 15.

659
00:49:35.559 --> 00:49:39.104
-  It's not that simple. Marge.
- Mmm.

660
00:49:44.193 --> 00:49:45.944
Eddie would never get up and lie.

661
00:49:46.028 --> 00:49:48.113
He went to Annapolis. Right?

662
00:49:48.197 --> 00:49:51.241
Duty. honor. country.
Those things matter to him.

663
00:49:52.784 --> 00:49:55.704
You don't have to go to Annapolis
to have integrity. Karen.

664
00:49:55.787 --> 00:49:58.957
No. I don't mean to imply that.
but I know my husband...

665
00:49:59.041 --> 00:50:00.626
Duty. honor. country.

666
00:50:02.085 --> 00:50:03.420
I believe in those things.

667
00:50:06.381 --> 00:50:07.424
Sometimes...

668
00:50:08.842 --> 00:50:10.427
you have to pick two.

669
00:50:19.102 --> 00:50:21.897
This is a very exciting time.

670
00:50:22.272 --> 00:50:25.567
Just one month ago.
Russian cosmonaut Alexei Leonov

671
00:50:25.651 --> 00:50:27.861
became the first man
to step foot on the moon.

672
00:50:28.779 --> 00:50:32.074
Now. American astronauts
Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin

673
00:50:32.533 --> 00:50:34.117
hope to do the same.

674
00:50:34.493 --> 00:50:38.121
Much preparation has been made
for this moment.

675
00:50:38.580 --> 00:50:42.209
Millions of people around the world
await their landing.

676
00:50:43.293 --> 00:50:45.712
Once they are on the moon's surface...

677
00:50:49.925 --> 00:50:51.468
Your father says he misses you.

678
00:50:53.053 --> 00:50:56.390
- He says you don't call. You don't write.

679
00:50:57.850 --> 00:50:59.518
You should go home and see him.

680
00:50:59.601 --> 00:51:00.644
I'll call.

681
00:51:01.603 --> 00:51:03.230
Have you no wish to go home?

682
00:51:03.772 --> 00:51:06.733
No sentimental attachments to Huntsville?

683
00:51:08.235 --> 00:51:10.070
To paraphrase a great man.

684
00:51:11.071 --> 00:51:15.075
- "Alabama is not a place for feelings."

685
00:51:15.993 --> 00:51:18.829
Your tongue will get you in trouble
one day. Margo.

686
00:51:19.454 --> 00:51:20.706
So I've heard.

687
00:51:24.126 --> 00:51:27.337
One minute
to reacquisition of signal from Apollo 11.

688
00:51:27.421 --> 00:51:28.922
One minute to reacquisition.

689
00:51:29.965 --> 00:51:33.010
All the work was for this moment.

690
00:51:33.760 --> 00:51:37.097
We are about to land a man on the moon.

691
00:51:42.477 --> 00:51:43.478
Come.

692
00:51:50.944 --> 00:51:52.279
Godspeed. Eagle.

693
00:51:54.364 --> 00:51:56.325
Eagle has begun its final descent...

694
00:51:56.408 --> 00:51:57.451
Final approach!

695
00:51:59.953 --> 00:52:00.996
Come on now. Neil.

696
00:52:01.079 --> 00:52:03.540
You got this. buddy! Right down the pipe!

697
00:52:04.249 --> 00:52:06.585
Okay. Gather round. gather round.
Come on. kids. Come on.

698
00:52:06.668 --> 00:52:08.962
-  Come on. Sit down. Shane.
- They're heading for the landing.

699
00:52:09.379 --> 00:52:10.589
Isn't this exciting?

700
00:52:10.672 --> 00:52:14.176
...two men to descend from orbit
to the moon's surface

701
00:52:14.259 --> 00:52:15.636
and then back up again.

702
00:52:15.719 --> 00:52:16.762
Cheers.

703
00:52:16.845 --> 00:52:18.514
It is a marvel of modern engineering.

704
00:52:25.312 --> 00:52:26.480
There it is.

705
00:52:27.856 --> 00:52:29.900
There is a crossing
half a mile to the east.

706
00:52:36.031 --> 00:52:37.157
This way.

707
00:52:40.035 --> 00:52:41.703
- Turn that off!

708
00:52:41.787 --> 00:52:43.288
Silence from now on!

709
00:52:51.129 --> 00:52:53.423
Beta ARM. Altitudes are a little high.

710
00:52:57.928 --> 00:53:00.973
Houston. I'm getting a little fluctuation
in the AC voltage now.

711
00:53:02.933 --> 00:53:05.394
Roger. Looks good to us.
You're still looking good at three.

712
00:53:05.477 --> 00:53:06.603
Coming up three minutes.

713
00:53:08.981 --> 00:53:11.942
Our position checks
downrange show us to be a little long.

714
00:53:21.493 --> 00:53:24.288
AGS has gone about two feet per second
greater than it should be.

715
00:53:26.206 --> 00:53:29.835
Roger. That still looks good to us.
You are go. You are go for landing.

716
00:53:29.918 --> 00:53:32.379
Roger. Understood. Go for landing.

717
00:53:34.631 --> 00:53:35.924
Three thousand feet.

718
00:53:37.050 --> 00:53:38.635
Eight hundred feet.

719
00:53:38.719 --> 00:53:41.054
Eight hundred feet.
Into the AGS. 47 degrees.

720
00:53:41.972 --> 00:53:43.724
Eagle. looking great. You're go.

721
00:53:45.058 --> 00:53:46.351
Thirty-five degrees.

722
00:53:47.728 --> 00:53:52.107
Thirty-five degrees.
750. Coming down to 23.

723
00:53:52.191 --> 00:53:53.400
Copy.

724
00:53:54.151 --> 00:53:56.612
Three hundred feet.
down three and a half. 47 forward.

725
00:53:58.238 --> 00:53:59.823
Altitude velocity light.

726
00:54:00.782 --> 00:54:01.992
Watch your shadow out there.

727
00:54:04.244 --> 00:54:05.579
I see the shadow.

728
00:54:06.455 --> 00:54:09.041
Wait. Got some boulders up ahead.

729
00:54:09.666 --> 00:54:10.667
Right in our path.

730
00:54:11.293 --> 00:54:13.879
I'm going long. looking for a better site.

731
00:54:14.379 --> 00:54:15.380
Thrusting forward.

732
00:54:16.632 --> 00:54:19.051
One hundred feet.
three and a half down. nine forward.

733
00:54:19.134 --> 00:54:20.302
Five percent.

734
00:54:20.761 --> 00:54:22.429
Control. how much fuel does he have left?

735
00:54:22.930 --> 00:54:24.014
Twenty seconds. Flight.

736
00:54:25.390 --> 00:54:26.433
Seventy-five feet.

737
00:54:27.100 --> 00:54:29.645
Rocks everywhere.
Still looking for a spot to set down.

738
00:54:30.312 --> 00:54:31.730
He's outside the safety margin.

739
00:54:33.565 --> 00:54:34.733
Should we abort?

740
00:54:37.069 --> 00:54:39.905
Neil knows the situation.
It's his spacecraft now.

741
00:54:42.407 --> 00:54:44.201
Lights on. Twenty feet.

742
00:54:45.244 --> 00:54:46.537
Kicking up some dust.

743
00:54:46.620 --> 00:54:48.455
- Lot of dust.
- Drifting right.

744
00:54:48.539 --> 00:54:49.540
Watch that one!

745
00:54:50.415 --> 00:54:51.458
Watch it!

746
00:54:52.167 --> 00:54:53.252
We've lost telemetry.

747
00:54:53.919 --> 00:54:54.920
No bioreadings!

748
00:54:55.796 --> 00:54:56.755
Lost contact.

749
00:54:56.839 --> 00:54:59.341
AGC is negative.
And no data from the onboard computer.

750
00:54:59.424 --> 00:55:00.801
Flight. I've got nothing here.

751
00:55:00.884 --> 00:55:02.427
- I've lost the whole board!
- No signal!

752
00:55:08.809 --> 00:55:10.894
Settle down. people. Settle!

753
00:55:12.980 --> 00:55:14.773
CAPCOM. see if you can raise the LEM.

754
00:55:15.858 --> 00:55:17.734
Eagle. Houston. Do you read?

755
00:55:20.028 --> 00:55:22.155
Eagle. this is Houston. Do you read?

756
00:55:27.828 --> 00:55:29.872
Eagle. this is Houston. do you copy?

757
00:55:31.456 --> 00:55:33.584
Eagle. Houston. Do you read?

758
00:55:33.667 --> 00:55:35.127
CAPCOM. see if Columbia can reach them.

759
00:55:35.878 --> 00:55:39.173
Columbia. Houston. We've lost contact
with the Eagle. See if you can raise them.

760
00:55:39.715 --> 00:55:41.175
Roger that. Houston.

761
00:55:41.258 --> 00:55:43.552
Eagle. Columbia. Do you read? Over.

762
00:55:45.804 --> 00:55:49.266
Eagle. this is Columbia.
Can you copy my transmission? Come back.

763
00:55:53.145 --> 00:55:54.396
Eagle. this is Columbia.

764
00:55:54.855 --> 00:55:56.064
How do you read?

765
00:56:02.696 --> 00:56:05.324
Eagle. this is Houston. Do you copy?

766
00:56:05.908 --> 00:56:06.909
Over.

767
00:56:12.998 --> 00:56:15.167
Is it possible the spacecraft exploded?

768
00:56:16.126 --> 00:56:17.878
Unlikely.

769
00:56:17.961 --> 00:56:19.379
If the LEM had exploded.

770
00:56:19.463 --> 00:56:21.340
we would have seen some precursor events

771
00:56:21.423 --> 00:56:23.342
in the telemetry stream
before we lost signal.

772
00:56:23.425 --> 00:56:26.386
They're outta fuel.
so they're definitely down.

773
00:56:26.470 --> 00:56:28.055
Maybe it was just communications.

774
00:56:28.138 --> 00:56:29.640
And all telemetry? No.

775
00:56:30.682 --> 00:56:32.434
These are independent systems.

776
00:56:32.518 --> 00:56:37.648
They could not fail simultaneously
unless there was a catastrophic event.

777
00:56:39.733 --> 00:56:40.859
So they crashed?

778
00:56:41.860 --> 00:56:43.153
Most likely.

779
00:56:44.947 --> 00:56:46.532
The skin on the Eagle is so thin.

780
00:56:46.615 --> 00:56:49.034
you could punch a hole in it
with a screwdriver.

781
00:56:52.579 --> 00:56:54.998
At least they were in their suits.

782
00:56:55.082 --> 00:56:57.876
So. they could've survived
a breach of the LEM's hull.

783
00:57:02.798 --> 00:57:05.676
If they are alive.
what's our contingency plan?

784
00:57:06.009 --> 00:57:07.845
There is no contingency plan.

785
00:57:07.928 --> 00:57:11.056
There is no way to effect a rescue
from the lunar surface.

786
00:57:11.974 --> 00:57:15.769
Columbia will pass over Tranquility
in 54 minutes.

787
00:57:16.562 --> 00:57:18.146
There's a telescope on board.

788
00:57:18.647 --> 00:57:20.357
Maybe Mike can see something from orbit.

789
00:57:21.441 --> 00:57:24.319
Eagle. this is Houston. Do you copy? Over.

790
00:57:33.412 --> 00:57:36.498
I'm coming up
on the Sea of Tranquility now.

791
00:57:36.582 --> 00:57:38.792
I'm following the surface terrain.

792
00:57:39.751 --> 00:57:42.337
I think the landing site
should be coming up soon.

793
00:57:43.046 --> 00:57:45.966
Can't see anything yet. Nothing.

794
00:57:47.217 --> 00:57:50.345
Can't see... Wait. There.

795
00:57:50.429 --> 00:57:52.097
Don't know if you can see this.

796
00:57:52.181 --> 00:57:53.473
I don't see anything.

797
00:57:53.557 --> 00:57:55.142
Mike's got a better view
through the scope.

798
00:57:55.225 --> 00:57:57.144
We're just looking at a shitty TV screen.

799
00:57:57.519 --> 00:57:59.605
I see Eagle.

800
00:58:00.022 --> 00:58:05.068
I'd say she's about six to eight miles
southwest to the targeted landing site.

801
00:58:05.152 --> 00:58:08.280
Seems to be in a pretty rocky area.

802
00:58:08.363 --> 00:58:10.324
Can't see any movement or activity.

803
00:58:10.407 --> 00:58:12.075
He wouldn't be able to from that altitude.

804
00:58:12.743 --> 00:58:14.411
At least we know where they are.

805
00:58:15.287 --> 00:58:17.956
Eagle. this is Houston. Do you copy? Over.

806
00:58:18.665 --> 00:58:21.543
Thousands have gathered
in cities across the world.

807
00:58:21.627 --> 00:58:26.048
waiting with bated breath for any word
on the fate of Apollo 11 and its crew.

808
00:58:26.131 --> 00:58:29.968
But as more time passes.
hope is beginning to fade.

809
00:58:30.052 --> 00:58:34.598
In Rome. Pope Paul led the faithful
in prayers for the return of the men.

810
00:58:34.681 --> 00:58:36.099
quoting the Ninth Psalm.

811
00:58:36.183 --> 00:58:39.728
"The Lord is a stronghold
in times of trouble."

812
00:58:42.231 --> 00:58:48.195
To recap: It's been over four hours since
radio contact with the Eagle was lost...

813
00:58:48.737 --> 00:58:51.490
Karen. you and Louanne
head over to the Aldrin house.

814
00:58:51.573 --> 00:58:53.617
Betty and Jackie. to the Collins.

815
00:58:53.700 --> 00:58:55.994
Linda. you come with me
over to the Armstrongs.

816
00:58:56.078 --> 00:58:57.746
There's gonna be a lot of press out there.

817
00:58:57.829 --> 00:58:59.790
but you just push past them
and say "No comment."

818
00:58:59.873 --> 00:59:01.625
Everyone else.
stay here with Tracy and the kids

819
00:59:01.708 --> 00:59:03.335
and hold down the fort. please.

820
00:59:03.836 --> 00:59:05.295
Stay by your phones.

821
00:59:06.129 --> 00:59:07.631
I think it's gonna be a long night.

822
00:59:09.716 --> 00:59:10.717
Let's go.

823
00:59:17.599 --> 00:59:18.433
Mr. President.

824
00:59:18.517 --> 00:59:20.978
after running various simulations

825
00:59:21.061 --> 00:59:22.104
it is our judgment

826
00:59:22.187 --> 00:59:24.231
that the likelihood of the astronauts

827
00:59:24.314 --> 00:59:26.859
having survived a crash of this nature

828
00:59:27.359 --> 00:59:28.986
...is very low.

829
00:59:29.069 --> 00:59:30.988
It's...

830
00:59:31.405 --> 00:59:32.656
such a tragedy.

831
00:59:32.739 --> 00:59:36.952
There is a statement that was
prepared for you in just this eventuality.

832
00:59:37.035 --> 00:59:38.078
Yeah. I've read it.

833
00:59:38.620 --> 00:59:39.454
I'll...

834
00:59:40.455 --> 00:59:43.417
alert the networks that I want
airtime to address the nation.

835
00:59:47.254 --> 00:59:48.839
"In ancient days..."

836
00:59:50.132 --> 00:59:51.592
...better ancient times. I think.

837
00:59:52.092 --> 00:59:53.844
"In ancient times..."

838
00:59:54.178 --> 00:59:58.599
"men looked at stars and saw their
heroes in the constellations."

839
00:59:59.558 --> 01:00:01.977
"In modern times we do much the same..."

840
01:00:02.728 --> 01:00:05.772
"but our heroes are epic men
of flesh and blood..."

841
01:00:07.024 --> 01:00:10.027
"and these men will remain
the foremost in our hearts."

842
01:00:10.777 --> 01:00:15.199
"For every human being who looks up
at the moon in the nights to come..."

843
01:00:16.116 --> 01:00:18.869
"will know that there is some corner
of another world..."

844
01:00:19.536 --> 01:00:21.413
"that is forever mankind."

845
01:00:23.040 --> 01:00:26.001
Okay. that's great.
We'll do it just like that.

846
01:00:59.159 --> 01:01:02.162
There's nothing left
for us to do in the back.

847
01:01:03.163 --> 01:01:04.540
so they let us go.

848
01:01:06.416 --> 01:01:08.126
There is an old superstition.

849
01:01:09.461 --> 01:01:12.256
Never drink to a success
before it happens.

850
01:01:12.881 --> 01:01:16.009
Not very scientific. but good advice.

851
01:01:16.093 --> 01:01:18.470
Doctor. we have a problem.

852
01:01:22.266 --> 01:01:24.893
Mike. I think we all understand
how you feel. but...

853
01:01:24.977 --> 01:01:28.355
All due respect. Houston.
I don't think you do understand.

854
01:01:28.438 --> 01:01:31.233
I decided a long time ago that
if something like this were to happen.

855
01:01:31.316 --> 01:01:33.026
that I wasn't coming home alone.

856
01:01:33.443 --> 01:01:35.070
I'm staying right where I am.

857
01:01:35.153 --> 01:01:36.572
Columbia. out.

858
01:01:37.155 --> 01:01:39.408
He doesn't get to make that decision.

859
01:01:39.491 --> 01:01:40.951
Give him a direct command. An order.

860
01:01:41.034 --> 01:01:43.996
The man's 200.000 miles away.
How you gonna enforce it?

861
01:01:44.079 --> 01:01:46.498
I am not calling the president
and telling him

862
01:01:46.582 --> 01:01:49.877
that Michael Collins refuses
to come home alone.

863
01:01:50.377 --> 01:01:52.004
Find his wife. Get her to talk to him.

864
01:01:52.087 --> 01:01:55.924
Oh. Jesus Christ. Please tell me
we are not gonna bring this man's wife in.

865
01:02:05.726 --> 01:02:08.729
Houston. Tranquility Base here.
Do you read? Over.

866
01:02:08.812 --> 01:02:10.772
Tranquility Base. Houston.
Neil. is that you?

867
01:02:11.190 --> 01:02:12.816
That's affirmative. Houston.

868
01:02:13.233 --> 01:02:16.236
Just wanted to let you know
that the Eagle has landed.

869
01:02:16.320 --> 01:02:18.447
She might have clipped a feather or two
on the way down.

870
01:02:18.530 --> 01:02:21.533
but she's still here. and so are we.

871
01:02:34.213 --> 01:02:35.589
Copy that. Tranquility.

872
01:02:35.672 --> 01:02:38.300
You just made a whole lot of people
very happy down here.

873
01:02:39.051 --> 01:02:40.636
Glad to hear it. Houston.

874
01:02:40.719 --> 01:02:43.472
We're pretty happy up here too.
to tell you the truth.

875
01:02:44.681 --> 01:02:46.683
I think I got this camera working. Neil.

876
01:02:49.603 --> 01:02:51.188
We have a picture. Eagle.

877
01:02:54.316 --> 01:02:55.651
Not one of my better landings.

878
01:02:56.568 --> 01:02:58.946
But like we used to say in the navy.

879
01:02:59.029 --> 01:03:01.532
any landing that you can walk away from
is a good one.

880
01:03:03.075 --> 01:03:04.243
We had a rough start.

881
01:03:04.326 --> 01:03:07.663
but we've decided to pick ourselves up
and get back to work.

882
01:03:13.043 --> 01:03:14.878
Well. we did it.

883
01:03:15.504 --> 01:03:16.922
We're on the moon.

884
01:03:17.305 --> 01:04:17.726
